The Telegraph - Calcutta
		 Tuesday, April 06, 2004  Champion horseman dies 
				 										London: Fred Winter, the only man to have won the Grand National, the Gold Cup and the Champion Hurdle as a jockey and trainer, died on Friday aged 77, the BBC reported on Monday.				 										Winter was champion National Hunt jockey four times and champion trainer on eight occasions, including five in succession between 1971 and 1975.				 										His first National success as a jockey came with Sundew in 1957. Five years later he landed the marathon race for a second time on board Kilmore.				 										As a trainer, Winter won the Aintree showpiece with Jay Trump in 1965 and followed up a year later with Anglo.				 										He won the Gold Cup as a jockey on Saffron Tartan in 1961 and Mandarin in 1962. He also trained Midnight Court to win the blue riband of steeplechasing in 1978. (REUTERS)

